        <p><lb n="1"/><unclear>śrī</unclear>-ghaṭ<unclear>o</unclear>tkaca<supplied reason="omitted">ḥ</supplied><supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> tad-va<sic>n</sic>śe prava<supplied cert="low" reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->rttamā</supplied><lb break="no" n="2"/><unclear>ne</unclear> mahāra<unclear>rā</unclear>ja-śrī-samu<unclear>dragu</unclear>pta<supplied reason="omitted">ḥ</supplied><supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> ta<unclear>t-pu</unclear><lb break="no" n="3"/><unclear>tra</unclear><supplied reason="omitted">ḥ</supplied> śrī-vikkramā<unclear>ditya</unclear><supplied reason="omitted">ḥ</supplied><supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> ta<unclear>tputra</unclear><supplied reason="omitted">ḥ</supplied> mahārā<supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->ja</supplied><lb break="no" n="4"/>-<unclear>śrī</unclear>-mahe<unclear>ndrāditya</unclear><supplied reason="omitted">ḥ</supplied><supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> tasya <unclear>pu</unclear>tra<supplied reason="omitted">ḥ</supplied> cakkra-<unclear>va</unclear><lb break="no" n="5"/><unclear>rtti</unclear>-tu<unclear>lyo</unclear> <unclear>mahā</unclear>-bala-vikkrameṇa r<unclear>āma</unclear><lb break="no" n="6"/>-<unclear>tu</unclear>lyo dha<unclear>rmma</unclear>-pa<unclear>ra</unclear>tayā yudhiṣṭira sa<unclear>tye</unclear><lb break="no" n="7"/>n<unclear>ā</unclear>c<unclear>ā</unclear>ravi<unclear>naya</unclear> mahārāja-śrī-ska<unclear>nda</unclear><lb break="no" n="8"/>guptasya rājya-<unclear>samva</unclear>tsara-śate Eka<lb break="no" n="9"/>-catvāri<unclear>nśotta</unclear>rake <!--
Bhandarkar suggests pravarttamāne or pravarddhamāne to restore the lacuna in line 1, but also notes that the damaged letter at the beginning of l2 looks more like nāṁ.
--><!--
In line 6, understand yudhiṣṭhira-tulyaḥ.
--><!--
In 6-7, understand satyenācāravinayaiḥ or better, satyācāravinayaiḥ (although this still looks garbled; if Ācāravinaya were a name, then the pattern would remain intact.
--><!--
In line 8, understand °guptaḥ| tasya.
--><!--
In line 9, understand catvāriṁśaduttarake
--></p>
        <p><unclear>asyāṁ</unclear> divasa-pū<lb break="no" n="10"/>rvvāyā<sic>ṁ</sic> Avaḍara-vāstavya-kuṭumbi<supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->kaḥ</supplied> <lb n="11"/>kaivartti-śreṣṭhi-<choice>
            <sic>naptr̥</sic>
            <corr>naptā</corr>
          </choice> hari-śreṣṭhi-pu<unclear>tra</unclear><supplied reason="omitted">ḥ</supplied> śrīda<lb break="no" n="12"/><unclear>tta</unclear><supplied reason="omitted">ḥ</supplied><supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> tad-<choice>
            <sic>bhrātr̥</sic>
            <corr>bhrātā</corr>
          </choice> vargga<supplied reason="omitted">ḥ</supplied><supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> ta<unclear>d-bhrā</unclear><choice>
            <sic>ta</sic>
            <corr>tā</corr>
          </choice> <choice>
            <sic>ccha</sic>
            <corr>cha</corr>
          </choice>ndaka <gap precision="low" quantity="3" reason="illegible" unit="character"/> <supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> <lb n="13"/>sva-puṇy-āpyāyan-ārthaṁ yaśaḥ-kī<lb break="no" n="14"/><unclear>rtti</unclear>-pravardhamāna-gottra-śailikā bala-ya<lb break="no" n="15"/><choice>
            <sic>ṣṭhi</sic>
            <corr>ṣṭiḥ</corr>
          </choice> pratiṣṭhāpitā vargga-grāmikeṇa<lb n="16"/><choice>
            <sic>je</sic>
            <corr>jye</corr>
          </choice>ṣṭha-māse śukla-pakṣasya dvitī<lb break="no" n="17"/><unclear>yāyāṁ</unclear> ti<unclear>thau</unclear><!--
Sircar restores the end of line 12 as chandakaś ceti. Bhandarkar (1981:319n1) remarks that there are three letters, most likely śalavyāṁ, probably a place name. Agrawala, however, thinks the most likely restoration is tadbhrātuś cchandakabhadrasya. In line 14, both Bhandarkar and Agrawala print pravardha[#ya]māna. There is certainly nothing like ya there, so apparently they want to emend the text to pravardhayamāna. I think that would be rather awkward and leave the text as it is; if we emend, then maybe we should be bolder and emend to pravardhanāya. Agrawala (1983:66n10) opines that balayaṣṭi means "a memorial pillar raised over a spot that enshrined the remains of the deceased" because bala is attested as meaning "enclosure," therefore "cavern, cave." Agrawala also adds that traces of a few more akṣaras after tithau at the end are visible, probably giving the date in numerals.
--></p>
